==English==

===Etymology 1===
Origin uncertain. According to the [http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=brat Online Etymology Dictionary], the term "brat" derives from an Old English (Old English) slang term meaning "beggar's child". Originally a dialectal word, from northern and western England and the Midlands, for a "makeshift or ragged garment"; probably the same word as {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|bratt||cloak|lang=ang}}, which is from a Celtic source (compare Old Irish {{term|bratt||cloak, cloth|lang=sga}}).

====Pronunciation====
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/bɹat/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{enPR|brăt}}, {{IPA|/bɹæt/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|æt|lang=en}}

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{context|pejorative|_|slang|lang=en}} A [[child]]; especially, one who is regarded as [[mischievous]], [[unruly]], [[spoil]]ed, or [[selfish]].
#: {{usex|Get that little '''brat''' away from me!|lang=en}}
# {{context|slang|lang=en}} A [[son]] or [[daughter]] (at any age) of an active [[military]] service member.
#: ''an army '''brat'''''
# a {{w|Turbot|turbot}} or [[flatfish]]
